attachments.fallback: [April 4th, 2020 2:59 PM] edenabate: On another extreme there has been real issues of getting family members not to come visit their loved ones at hospitals when they are confirmed positive. It’s embedded in our culture to visit when someone is sick however the risk involved is not one that is resonating with people.  Several myths affecting this issue that we can address, is “the idea that this is just a flu so this is nothing i can handle it ideology” or the “ I am young so I am immune or it won’t affect me as much” , because they ask if the young ones could go in and visit.  “the concept of not taking care of your loved one or showing up being seen as lack of love and even the concept of it’s better to die together.” So creating awareness around the risk of visiting a loved one or burying a loved one during this time is a taxing issue that needs to be addressed in multiple languages.

text: <@U010UM8QBQA> just did shopping and donation for an old couple for a months supply did it from Atiklit Tera and buying it from whole sellers in Mercato not sure if it would work on your excel sheet but def happy to share my cost and calculation. In addition my recommendation is to focus on local ingredients people know how to make it last and the portions are already engrained in us. A lot of the groups donating have been focusing on buying dirkosh in kilos as it preserves longer and is easy to make. Avoid Bole I shop there frequently and have seen prices becoming ridiculously  inflated these days. Will try and reach out to the whole sellers that supply the market  and see if they are willing to help us.
